# TCP and UDP - 3-Way Handshake

## TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)

### Characteristics
| Feature | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Reliability | Guaranteed delivery, retransmits lost packets |
| Ordering | Packets arrive in sequence |
| Connection-oriented | 3-way handshake before data transfer |
| Flow Control | Prevents sender from overwhelming receiver |
| Error Checking | Checksum and acknowledgment |
| Use Cases | Web browsing, email, file transfer, messaging |

---

### TCP 3-Way Handshake

The three-way handshake establishes a reliable connection before data transfer.











---

## TCP vs UDP Comparison

| Aspect | TCP | UDP |
|--------|-----|-----|
| Connection | Connection-oriented | Connectionless |
| Reliability | Reliable (retransmission) | Unreliable (no retransmission) |
| Ordering | Ordered | Unordered |
| Flow Control | Yes | No |
| Error Recovery | Yes | No (only checksum) |
| Header Size | 20 bytes | 8 bytes |
| Speed | Slower | Faster |
| Use Case | Web, email, file transfer | Voice, video, streaming, gaming |

---

## Real-World Examples

### TCP Example: Telegram Text Message
You send "Hello" as a text message:
1. TCP handshake establishes connection
2. Message segmented into packets with sequence numbers
3. Each packet acknowledged by server
4. If packet lost, it's retransmitted
5. All packets reassembled in correct order
6. You see single checkmark (sent), then double checkmark (delivered)

### UDP Example: Telegram Voice Call
You say "Hello" during a voice call:
1. No handshake - data sent immediately
2. Voice audio broken into datagrams
3. No acknowledgment of receipt
4. If datagram lost, it's gone (tiny audio glitch)
5. Datagrams may arrive out of order (still playable)
6. Call continues without delay

### Why Voice Calls Use UDP
- Speed is critical (real-time)
- Retransmission would cause delay
- Small glitches are acceptable
- TCP would cause noticeable lag
